# dry-refactoring-plan-assumption-audit — History

## v2.2.0 (2026-06-26)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus issue #1409 planning (extract shared validation CLI parser helper)
**Verification:** unverified — planning-stage learning only; implementation and CI were not executed.

### What changed

- Minor bump from v2.1.0 to v2.2.0.
- Added the shared validation CLI parser extraction case to the description, tags, When to Use, Quick Reference, Detailed Steps, Failed Attempts, Results, and Verified On sections.
- Captured the plan's highest-risk assumptions: issue count drift (issue said 16 validation files; current discovery cited 12 exact `--repo-root` matches), parser subclass behavior, `parse_known_args()` pass-through behavior, `__all__`/barrel export parity, and structural-grep false confidence.
- Added a copy-paste parser extraction audit checklist for plan reviewers and implementers.

### Why

This belongs in the existing DRY refactoring planning audit because the search surface is the same: a behavior-preserving consolidation plan where stale issue evidence, incomplete population discovery, and unverified call-contract assumptions can make a mechanically plausible refactor unsafe. Someone reviewing a DRY extraction of repeated validation CLI parser setup should land here before approving the plan.

### Previous version (v2.1.0) snapshot

The full v2.1.0 text is preserved in git history at the commit preceding this amendment. v2.1.0 covered module-consolidation risks for `__all__`, early exits, test delegation shims, dependency assumptions, same-name signature collisions, TOML section-boundary regex behavior, and verified test counts. v2.2.0 leaves those lessons intact and adds the shared validation CLI parser planning-risk layer.

